# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: birmingham-children-s-hospital
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/1-7-constitution-hill-birmingham] It was designed in 1895 and 1896 by William Doubleday and James R.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/1-7-constitution-hill-birmingham] Sale, a die-sinker firm that as of 2012 occupies premises on Summer Lane within 100 metres of the original building.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/1-7-constitution-hill-birmingham] The original plans were for five stories, but only four were built.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/1-7-constitution-hill-birmingham] A fifth storey was added in the mid-20th century before planning laws were in force to protect the integrity of original structures and as a result, the fifth floor is not of the same architectural style of the 1895 building.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/1-7-constitution-hill-birmingham] The tower is original, built in 1896 as a memorial to Lord Roberts of Kandahar (1832–1914) who led a successful campaign in Afghanistan in 1879 before a career in India.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/1-7-constitution-hill-birmingham] Plans show three independent shops and offices at ground level.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/1-7-constitution-hill-birmingham] Each upper floor, measuring approximately 900 square feet (84 m2), was designed as a single workshop with an office in the tower.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/1-7-constitution-hill-birmingham] There was an engine room and dynamo in the basement.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/1-7-constitution-hill-birmingham] The present owner also purchased the adjacent buildings numbers 9-11 Constitution Hill in the early 1990s in order to provide better access to the listed main body of the property.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/1-7-constitution-hill-birmingham] Known locally as the 'Red Palace', the building as of 2007 was only occupied on the top two floors.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/1-7-constitution-hill-birmingham] The lower floors remained empty after the previous tenant, a Chinese restaurant trading as 'China Village', vacated in approximately 2002.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/1-7-constitution-hill-birmingham] The basement floor was used as the kitchens serving the main restaurant on the ground floor and function room on the first floor.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/1-7-constitution-hill-birmingham] The building fabric has been deteriorating for a number of years and needs a significant investment if the building is to survive long term.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/1-7-constitution-hill-birmingham] The ground and first floor re-opened as a Syrian/Lebanese restaurant called 'Syriana' in April 2008.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/1-7-constitution-hill-birmingham] In January 2026, the building was the scene of a major fire, requiring the attendance of over 30 firefighters.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] It has 39 floors, and is the third tallest structure in the city after the 499 ft (152 m) British Telecom Tower and the 433 ft (132 m) The Mercian.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] The front façade of the building is floor-to-ceiling glass decorated in "tiger stripes" which are used to enhance the vertical impact.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] As the apartments were being furbished, an aqua coloured camouflage was also added to these windows with some of the tiger stripes being removed.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] Coloured lights can be seen underneath the overhang at night.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] The lower 19-floors are a Radisson Blu hotel, which opened to guests on 16 January 2006 whilst the upper floors were still being furnished.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] The upper 20 floors contain 158 apartments.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] There are eight circular concrete columns as well as the core on each floor.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] The post-tensioned flat plates of the upper floors are concrete and measure 9 in (225 mm) in thickness.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] 10 Holloway Circus received 12 points in the 2006 Emporis Skyscraper Awards placing it in eighth position in the top ten.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] The plans for the development were first revealed in 1998 as part of a competition in which designs for a tower acting as a gateway to the city centre were to be submitted to the council and also for a building that could aid the regeneration plans in and around the area.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] The site chosen was the AEU Building, designed by The John Madin Design Group and completed in 1957, at Holloway Circus.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] Two serious proposals were put forward, one by Cala Homes, which consisted of two cylindrical glass towers, and the other by the Beetham Corporation, which was a single 44-storey tower with two spires on the roof producing a total height of 630 feet (192 m).
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] The Beetham Corporation won, however it was forced to scale down the towers height, due to height limits enforced after the September 11 terrorist attacks on the World Trade Center, by the Civil Aviation Authority.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] The spires were also removed and replaced by two cones placed on the rear of the tower on top of the stairwells.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] The proposed office space was also removed and the planning application was withdrawn.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] The new design was submitted, however, was withdrawn by the Beetham Corporation after talks over the purchase of the adjacent multi-storey car park with National Car Parks broke down without a deal.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] This was a surprise to the developers as they had expected to be able to purchase the land and had even included their plans for the site in the previous planning application.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] Amendments to the planning application were made and it was resubmitted in October 2000.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] The final design was approved by the Planning Department at Birmingham City Council with conditions on 3 April 2003 after the Beetham Corporation paid £1.8 million under Section 106 to gain planning approval.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] A model of the tower was tested in a wind tunnel with models of surrounding buildings also being included.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] The ground of the model was also accurate to that of the Birmingham landscape.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] The model passed with few problems and construction of the tower began.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] Construction began in March 2003 with the erection of hoardings around the site allowing clearance work to commence and the construction of a tower crane.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] The concrete core then began to rise and reached a considerable height before the construction of the concrete floor panels began.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] The transportation of materials to the higher levels were done using a lift attached to the middle of the curved frontage.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] That area was intended to be used as a staircase in the case of an emergency.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] The construction of the building encountered several problems.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] Not far into the construction of the lift shaft, a piece of scaffolding became dislodged and fell to the ground causing traffic delays around Holloway Circus which subsequently resulted in widespread disruption in the city centre.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] On 24 November 2005, 5 pieces of cladding from the higher levels on the sides became detached from the building and fell to the ground.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] No injuries were caused, however fear of more panels falling off caused nearby roads to be closed for an entire weekend, until the site could be declared safe by inspectors.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] Clips were later installed to secure the panels, and as of mid-2006, work was underway to permanently secure the panels in place using new clips.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] The securing of the panels was completed in late-August 2006.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] The Beetham Corporation could now face legal action due to the structure causing road closures and subsequent congestion.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] Excluding the problems with the panel clips, construction of the floors took ten months.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] Concrete was the primary material in the construction of the structure.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] The Beetham Organisation again faced legal action over claims by people who signed contracts to buy flats before the tower was completed that the flats they received did not match those described in the sales literature.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] As a result of technical problems within the underground car park, resident's cars were trapped for three days.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] Cars are placed on a platform and are taken into a space by a computer when the owner's card is swiped, however, glitches meant that people who had purchased spaces within the park either could not get access to their cars or were unable to enter the car park in their vehicles.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] 10 Holloway Circus faced yet more problems when, on 8 July 2007, a glass panel shattered and sent pieces raining 60 feet (18 m) onto the ground.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] The 6 ft (1.8 m) by 3 ft (0.91 m) panel on the eighth floor of Beetham Tower is believed to have shattered due to a build up of chemical compounds inside the glass.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] Splinters fell onto the car park roof and Smallbrook Queensway at about 6.30 am.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/10-holloway-circus] It was the third safety incident at the tower in three years.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] 103 Colmore Row is the tallest office building in the United Kingdom outside London to be constructed since the completion of Alpha Tower, also in Birmingham, in 1973.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] The original building was a 23-storey structure with entrances on Colmore Row and Newhall Street.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] Designed by John Madin, it is of the Brutalist style, contrasting the traditional Victorian architectural styles in the immediate area.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] Although, the pre-cast concrete panels on the exterior, which were common on commercial buildings of the time, rather than in-situ concrete did make the building differ from classic Brutalism.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] Designs for the building were first publicised in 1964 and it was remarked that it had drawn inspiration from the University of Pittsburgh by Louis Kahn.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] The designs showed a two-storey banking hall with a rectangular tower with horizontal ribbon windows.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] It also showed a service tower facing on to Newhall Street.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] This design differed significantly to the one that was approved by Birmingham City Council.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] The scheme also included a five-storey office block to the west of the site that was separated from it by an L-shaped courtyard.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] This office block was later reclad and increased to eight storeys in 1996-7 so that it reads as a separate building.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] The entire scheme was named the "Colmore Centre".
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] The first phase of the scheme, which consisted of the construction of the banking hall, was completed in 1969.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] Construction of the tower began in 1973 and was completed three years later at a total cost of £3.5 million.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] The building was constructed so that it was not solely occupied by the National Westminster Bank, but could also be let to tenants so that the bank could maximise the profitability of the site.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] However, the building proved difficult to let and was never fully occupied; the only other major corporation to take office space in the tower was Eversheds.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] The building had been vacant since 2003.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] There were numerous features of note, including the original aluminium-cast banking hall doors, created and made by Henry Haig (1930 – 6 December 2007), who was an English abstract artist, painter and sculptor, notable predominantly for his stained glass work.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] The doors consisted of an abstract triangle design based on the NatWest logo and were painted to resemble bronze.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] The banking hall itself had a coffered ceiling of plasterboard covered in gold leaf and Travertine marble floors and skirtings.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] The exterior was covered in abstract plaster murals and bronze matt ceramic tiles.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] The lift shaft and two ventilation towers were constructed using brick.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] The structure was constructed of precast concrete with waffle concrete floor slabs.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] There were four plant floors at the top of the tower and 100 car park spaces in a basement car park that became disused upon the discovery of asbestos.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] The office block was accessed via a stainless steel surround doorway on Newhall Street, where the land began to drop, exposing the ventilation grills for the basement.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] The entrance here appeared to be of a later date to the rest of the building.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] The office block had a service core at the centre of each floor, consisting of a large service duct, lavatories, four lift shafts and staircase.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] The lifts had stainless steel doors and the lift lobby had Travertine panelling on the walls.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] There was a kitchen on the twentieth floor which retained its original green panels and equipment, such as the dumbwaiter.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] The NatWest logo was originally attached to the west side of the building, although it was later removed leaving only the bracketing.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] It is believed that considerable efforts were made to reduce the cost of the tower's construction, which took place during a time when rising oil prices ended the development boom of the 1960s making an increasingly hostile economic climate.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] Examples of cost-cutting measures employed during the construction of the building include the use of plasterboard to mimic concrete on the banking hall's ceiling and the use of an alternative metal to bronze for the banking hall doors.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] The building was a prominent feature on the Birmingham skyline until its demolition.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] It was also one of the most modern buildings and the tallest structure in the Colmore Row and Environs Conservation Area, and became a frequent perching point for the city centre's peregrine falcons.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] In December 2006 British Land acquired the freehold of the tower from Omega Land for £25 million.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] A planning application was submitted in April 2008 for demolition of the existing tower and replacement with a 35-storey office building with ground floor retail.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] The proposed building would be 134.5 m to roof level and 159.5 m to the top of a light mast on the side of the tower.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] Designed by Hamilton Architects the projected cost was £160 million.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] The proposal initially received the backing of the Birmingham Civic Society who said that they were 90% happy with the design, however the organisation reversed their decision.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] The project also met objections from the Twentieth Century Society and the Victorian Society who commented that they were "extremely disappointed" with the proposal.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] After the public consultation, unsuccessful efforts were made to grant the building listed status from English Heritage.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] It was concluded that the building had good qualities of massing but lacked the high degree of sophisticated architectural detailing that would be expected of a building from this period.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] They also said that modifications made to the building in the 1990s had considerably compromised the building's architecture and that the interior lacked coherence, although they did comment that the interior of the banking hall did contain many interesting original features.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] The building received a Certificate of Immunity from Listing in October 2008 which would last until October 2013.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] The proposal received planning permission from Birmingham City Council in September 2008.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] It was closely contested with six councillors voting against the scheme and seven voting for it.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] Due to the effects of the 2008 financial crisis, British Land could not progress the approved scheme, planning permission expired in 2011 and the building was sold in 2014.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] On 29 September 2014 the building received another Certificate of Immunity from Listing to be effective until 28 September 2019.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] The remaining parts of the building do not have the detailed finish or overall architectural quality which would be expected of a structure of this date which was recommended for designation.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] The repetition of the pre-cast panels across the building creates an impression of regimentation and the turning of the corners is poorly handled.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] This is particularly apparent on the bank building, where the external treatment of the third floor is ungainly and the edges of the canted corners appear unduly clumsy and unresolved.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] And while the interior of the banking hall is of interest, it is not matched by the interiors elsewhere, which lack coherence and aesthetic quality." In November 2014 owners British Land sold the building to Sterling Property Ventures and Rockspring as development partners.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] The purchase price was not disclosed however it is thought to be in the region of £15 million.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] In June 2015 a planning application was submitted to demolish the existing tower and replace with a new 26 storey tower.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] The proposed £60 million steel, aluminium and glazed building, designed by Doone Silver Kerr, will provide a net floor area of 19,600 m2 (211,000 sq ft).
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] The building will be the tallest office building in Birmingham at 108 metres.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] It will comprise 18,200 m2 (196,000 sq ft) of office space over 19 floors, with floor plates up to 1,070 m2 (11,500 sq ft), and a terrace on the 18th level.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] A restaurant and retail will be provided at street level and a double height 800 m2 (8,600 sq ft) restaurant will be located at the top of the building.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] In all, the proposals outline 1,400 m2 (15,000 sq ft) of leisure space.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] The existing cast aluminium Natwest banking hall doors created and made by Henry Haig, will be incorporated into the new building in a prominent publicly accessible space at the request of the Haig family.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] Initial scaffolding for demolition began to be erected in July 2015 and a tower crane was installed on 20 September 2015.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] Demolition took place between September 2015 and January 2017.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] In February 2018 it was announced that Royal BAM Group had won an £80 million contract to build the new tower.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/103-colmore-row] Work started in June 2019, with a completion date of 2021.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/17-19-newhall-street-birmingham] Opened in 1887, the building was designed by Frederick Martin of the firm Martin & Chamberlain.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/17-19-newhall-street-birmingham] It was constructed to house the new Central Telephone Exchange and offices for the National Telephone Company (NTC).
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/17-19-newhall-street-birmingham] Birmingham's central exchange had 5,000 subscribers and was the largest of its type in the country.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/17-19-newhall-street-birmingham] Originally having the postal address of *19 Newhall Street*, it was known as "Telephone Buildings" within the NTC organisation but it was also popularly known as the "Bell Edison Telephone Building" – the NTC logo behind the wrought iron gates to the main entrance bears the names of Bell and Edison.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/17-19-newhall-street-birmingham] The ground floor of the building was let out to shops.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/17-19-newhall-street-birmingham] In 1912, the NTC was taken over by the Postmaster General and ownership of the building transferred to the GPO.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/17-19-newhall-street-birmingham] Whereas Telephone House accommodated the telex automatic exchange, 19 Newhall Street held a TAS exchange which was used by the GPO to route telegrams around the UK.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/17-19-newhall-street-birmingham] It also housed the Birmingham office of the Post Office Engineering Union (located on the basement floor in Edmund Street).
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/17-19-newhall-street-birmingham] During World War I, the building was used as the Midland headquarters of the air raid warning system.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/17-19-newhall-street-birmingham] In 1936, the Central Telephone Exchange vacated the building and relocated to new premises (Telephone House) further down Newhall Street.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/17-19-newhall-street-birmingham] 17 & 19 Newhall Street is now occupied by Core Marketing (a marketing and PR company), Mitchell Adam (an accountancy recruitment firm) and GBR Phoenix Beard (a firm of property consultants).
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/17-19-newhall-street-birmingham] The basement is occupied by a bar called *Bushwackers*, which has its entrance on Edmund Street.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/17-19-newhall-street-birmingham] The building's full postal address is: *The Exchange, 19 Newhall Street, Birmingham B3 3PJ*.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/17-19-newhall-street-birmingham] However, it occupies 17 & 19 Newhall Street as well as 103 Edmund Street.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/adam-eve-birmingham] The **Adam & Eve** is a former public house located on the corner of Bradford Street and Warner Street, in Deritend, Birmingham, England.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/adam-eve-birmingham] There had been a public house of this name in this location for at least 200 years.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/adam-eve-birmingham] The *Adam & Eve* is an uncommon pub name.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/adam-eve-birmingham] However, it is connected to the drinks trade through the Worshipful Company of Fruiterers who incorporated Adam and Eve in their crest.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/adam-eve-birmingham] The future site of the Adam & Eve is marked on an estate plan drawn by Samuel Bradford in 1748.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/adam-eve-birmingham] However its first recorded licensee, John Robinson, does not appear in the Warwick Licensing and Justices records until 1801.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/adam-eve-birmingham] Pubs in Deritend were also licensed by Bordesley magistrates but their names were not recorded.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/adam-eve-birmingham] Robinson appears in these records for 1787–1800 and so may also have been the landlord during this period.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/adam-eve-birmingham] The original building's layout is described in an 1837 rate book for Aston.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/adam-eve-birmingham] This lists a back-part, a washhouse, a stable and a house fronting Warner Street, as each part of the property was subjected to a separate rate.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/adam-eve-birmingham] In 1889, the Adam & Eve was taken over by the Brewers Investment Corporation Ltd who set about remodelling it.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/adam-eve-birmingham] Large windows and fascia boards were added, making it similar to other pubs of the time.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/adam-eve-birmingham] The internal floor space was restructured and an outdoor department was created.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/adam-eve-birmingham] Toilets were also constructed in the rear yard.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/adam-eve-birmingham] Further modifications were made to the building in 1921 and 1928 when a smoke room and kitchen were added.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/adam-eve-birmingham] An assembly room and dining room were also opened on the first floor.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/adam-eve-birmingham] The new layout also incorporated indoor toilets, which made the pub rather up-market for the time.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/adam-eve-birmingham] The Adam & Eve was severely damaged during the Birmingham Blitz and was never fully restored.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/adam-eve-birmingham] Many of its neighbouring buildings were completely destroyed.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/adam-eve-birmingham] The Adam & Eve ceased trading as a public house in 2015, following a triple stabbing incident in October of the previous year.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/adam-eve-birmingham] The premises were put up for auction and bought by a social housing trust who converted them into residential accommodation.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/adam-eve-birmingham] In 2018 a not for profit coffee shop was opened on the ground floor.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The site was previously occupied by a mansion known as Alder Hey which the local poor law guardians acquired for use as a children's home in 1910.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The mansion was converted for use as a military hospital in 1914.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] During the First World War, the United States Army established Camp Hospital 40 on the site, operated by Hospital Unit Q and, subsequently, Unit W.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] American sources commonly refer to Alder Hey as being within Liverpool's Knotty Ash area.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] During the Second World War, parts of the hospital were again used to treat injured military personnel.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The Liverpool Neonatal Surgical Unit opened at the hospital in 1953.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] This unit was the first neonatal intensive care unit in the United Kingdom.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The opening was largely due to the efforts of Isabella Forshall, a paediatric surgeon.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 1990 when Myrtle Street Children's Hospital (founded in 1869 and previously known as Royal Liverpool Children's Hospital) closed, Alder Hey absorbed its A&E department.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The hospital authority was one of 57 such bodies which became an NHS hospital trust in 1991.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Ronald McDonald House, a home for the families of sick children, opened in 1993.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 1999 an inquiry was instituted into the Alder Hey organs scandal and to investigate the hospital's practices in respect of removal and retention of human tissue.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The inquiry had far-reaching effects throughout the UK hospital system and provided the impetus for the Human Tissue Act 2004.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In August 2008 the Royal Liverpool Children's NHS Trust became an NHS foundation trust and changed its name to Alder Hey NHS Foundation Trust.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Between 2010 and 2014 the number of doctors employed at the trust increased from 269 to 344, while the number of managers increased from 70 to 86.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] At the end of March 2017, the trust was confirmed as one of four additional NHS Global Digital Exemplars, joining the twelve announced in September 2016.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey had its centenary year in 2014, the last year in which it operated from the buildings on its original site.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] A new hospital was procured under Private Finance Initiative contract in neighbouring Springfield Park.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The works, which were carried out by Laing O'Rourke at a cost of £187 million, began on 26 March 2013 and the hospital opened in October 2015.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It was Europe's first children's hospital built in a park.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The original Alder Hey buildings were mostly demolished and the land was reclaimed as new parkland for the surrounding community.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Features of the new hospital include access to play areas, natural light and striking views of the park are available wherever possible Children and young people were involved with the design of the new hospital.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] A drawing of a flower by teenage patient Eleanor Brogan impressed architects and inspired their final design.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The hospital is a centre of excellence for oncology and muscular dystrophy as well as spinal, heart and brain conditions.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey has Europe's first 3T Intraoperative MRI scanner which is a pioneering technology for neurosurgery, providing surgeons with extremely high resolution images and reducing the need for repeat operations in 90% of cases.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It currently employs about 2,400 staff and treats over 270,000 children from across the UK each year.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey conducts paediatric research into children's medicines, infection, inflammation and oncology.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It has research partners including the University of Liverpool and is a member of Liverpool Health Partners.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey conducts more than 100 clinical research studies on an ongoing basis, ranging from observation to clinical trials.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The hospital is within the National Institute for Health and Care Research's Top 100 Performing Trust's for participation recruitment in 2013/14.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey was a finalist in the Clinical Research Impact category of the 2013 HSJ Awards and in 2014 the innovation team received the Health Service Journal Award for improving health care with technology.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 2016 the first phase of a bespoke research, education and innovation centre, Institute in the Park, opened next to Alder Hey in the Park.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In November 2015, the institute hosted a children's health Hackathon in conjunction with Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey Children's Charity supports the work of the hospital.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In addition to NHS funding which covers the running costs of the hospital, Alder Hey relies on charitable support.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Funds are spent directly on initiatives in the hospital to benefit patients.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It funds research initiatives, patient and family enhancements and state of the art medical equipment.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Known as the 'Imagine Appeal' until 2012, Alder Hey Children's Charity is based within the hospital.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] On 14 October 2013 the charity launched a public appeal to raise £30m to fund equipment, facilities and research at Alder Hey's new hospital, Alder Hey in the Park.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In October 2015 the charity announced over £20m had been raised.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 2009 charitable support allowed Alder Hey to buy Europe's first 3T intraoperative MRI scanner.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In one charitably funded project, the sound recordist and musician Chris Watson was employed to devise an art project, using bird song recordings made by children to calm other young patients as they received injections and other treatments.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 1978, the charity Art For Their Sake, a team of volunteer artists led by founder George Nicholas (now of Ormskirk, England), produced the world's longest mural in the corridors of Alder Hey Children's Hospital.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] A Guinness Record was set with a total of 17,963 square feet of murals, and awarded to the hospital in 1986.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Nicholas and his team continued to work on these murals for a period of 30 years, adding to as well as restoring and maintaining, for a total of over 34,000 square feet.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey runs an Arts for Health programme, funded entirely through charitable sources including Alder Hey Children's Charity.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The programme aims to enhance the experience of being a patient and includes animation projects, music and dance therapy, creative writing, comedy workshops and storytelling.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] An international child health development programme led by Alder Hey clinicians focuses on humanitarian work in developing countries.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The programme includes provision of immediate medical support, knowledge sharing and involvement with international clinical trials.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The programme has undertaken work across Africa and Asia, including Pakistan, Malawi, Nepal and India.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] During the 1990s, Alder Hey was featured in the BBC television series *Children's Hospital*.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 2011, chef Heston Blumenthal took to the challenge of changing the dinner menu of Alder Hey Children's Hospital on his televised show, *Heston's Mission Impossible*.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Since September 2012, Alder Hey has regularly featured on the CBBC television series *Operation Ouch!*.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In October 2013, the Care Quality Commission's Intelligent Monitoring system placed Alder Hey in category one, meaning it would be amongst the first hospitals to be inspected under a new style of inspection.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In May 2014, Alder Hey was inspected by the Care Quality Commission and was given the overall rating Requires Improvement.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In June 2015, Alder Hey was re-inspected by the Care Quality Commission and was given the overall rating Good, and was rated Outstanding in the Caring category.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Another inspection took place in 2018, the overall rating was unchanged.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Dame Josephine Williams was appointed Chair of the Trust Board in February 2019.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Louise Shepherd CBE was appointed Chief Executive of the trust in March 2008.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] On 26 January 2023, the Alder Hey Children's Hospital NHS Foundation Trust was granted the Honorary Freedom of the Metropolitan Borough of Sefton.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] In May 2020, the stadium underwent a £72 million redevelopment which was completed in April 2022 ahead of the 2022 Commonwealth Games.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] The venue hosted the opening and closing ceremonies, as well as the athletics and para-athletics competitions of the 2022 Commonwealth Games in Birmingham.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] The main stadium has a nine lane category 1 World Athletics certified track.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] The stadium has an additional 6 lane warm up track and separate throws field.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] The West Stand offers 6 hospitality boxes, hospitality lounge with a capacity of 450 with track views and a multitude of track level spaces for hire.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] Other events held there include the annual British Grand Prix between 2011 and 2019 and in 2022, the Amateur Athletics Association Championships, the 1998 Disability World Athletics Championships, and the English Schools' Athletics Championships.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] The Stadium also hosted Midlands Hurricanes rugby league team from 2023 to 2025.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] It is the home Stadium of Athletics Club Birchfield Harriers replacing their former home at Alexander Sports Ground.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] The stadium will host the 2026 European Athletics Championships, the first time the continental championships will be held in the United Kingdom.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] The stadium currently has a seating capacity of 18,000.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] Seating capacity is split between Lower, Upper and VIP Box Level seating of the West stand, Lower and Upper seating in the East Stand and Lower Seating stands in the North and South.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] Before redevelopment, there were 7,000 covered seats in three separate stands called Main, Knowles (after Dick Knowles), and Nelson (after Doris Nelson Neal OBE), and a 5,000-seater stand on the rear straight.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] Since May 2023, Alexander Stadium has offered a wide range of rooms to hire for corporate, community and sporting events.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] Alexander Stadium is open to the public as a Birmingham City Council-run leisure centre.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] Alexander Stadium offers a range of activities such as Fitness Classes, Martial Arts, Athletics and Gymnastics.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] Classes can be booked via the website or contacting the Stadium directly.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] Birmingham City Council also offer a variety of memberships and free activity sessions inline with government initiatives such as Be Active and Passport to Leisure for lower income households within Birmingham.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] From 2011 Alexander Stadium hosted the prestigious world athletics Diamond League tour until 2019 ahead of the redevelopment.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] Birmingham held an event of the 2022 tour on 21 May 2022.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] The stadium has held many music events, including a one-day festival called Party in the Park run by BRMB (now Hits Radio Birmingham) radio that featured acts including Nelly Furtado, Westlife, Natasha Bedingfield, Blue, Sugababes, Debbie McGee, Girls Aloud and The Calling.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] The event was later moved to Cannon Hill Park where it was in a more central part of the city and so made it easier for people from south Birmingham to attend.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] In 2011 Alexander Stadium underwent a £12.5 million expansion and refurbishment, including the building of a 5,000-seater stand opposite the current main stand.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] The new stand has also become home to the offices of UK Athletics.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] The stand was completed in June 2011, in time to host the Diamond League British Grand Prix in July 2011.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] In June 2017, during the preparation of the Birmingham bid for the 2022 Commonwealth Games, the Birmingham bid committee proposed to renovate Alexander Stadium and use it for hosting the athletics and ceremonies of the Games.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] On 11 April 2018, British Prime Minister Theresa May announced that £70 million (approx.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] USD $90 million) of investment would be earmarked to transform the Alexander Stadium into a world-class athletics venue for the 2022 Commonwealth Games, during which it will seat 40,000 spectators.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] In October 2018, British engineering and designing firm Arup was chosen by the Birmingham City Council to redesign the stadium.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] British construction firm Mace was chosen to manage the stadium renovation project.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] On 21 June 2019, Birmingham City Council released the images and plans for renovating the Alexander Stadium and claimed that it would create a legacy asset for the Perry Barr area.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] On 30 January 2020, Birmingham City Council's planning committee approved the renovation plans of the Alexander Stadium which would cost £72 million.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] After the games, the temporary stands around the track bends were removed, leaving the two permanent stands seating 18,000, with the option of extending to 40,000 for major events.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] In March 2020, the city council chose the Northern Irish firm McLaughlin & Harvey to redevelop the stadium.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] Alexander Stadium was the main venue for athletics, para-athletics as well as holding the opening and closing ceremonies of the 2022 Commonwealth Games.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] The redeveloped stadium included temporary seating and facilities to accommodate the Games.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] Following the awarding of the 2026 European Athletics Championships to Birmingham, Alexander Stadium will serve as the venue for the championships.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] On 22 March 2016 fell-runner Lauren Jeska from Lancaster attacked UK Athletics official Ralph Knibbs at the stadium, stabbing him multiple times.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] Jeska had feared her records in women's events would be quashed due to her transgender identity.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] She later pleaded guilty to attempted murder and was sentenced to 18 years' imprisonment.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/alexander-stadium] She was also convicted of causing actual bodily harm to two bystanders who tried to defend Knibbs.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The hospital was founded by Thomas Pretious Heslop as the *Birmingham and Midland Free Hospital for Sick Children* at 138–9 Steelhouse Lane in 1862.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] It moved to a new site on Ladywood Middleway in 1917.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] In March 1986, a charity concert was held called "Heart Beat 86" at the nearby National Exhibition Centre, featuring George Harrison, which raised money for the hospital.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] In October 1998 the hospital returned to Steelhouse Lane, to the buildings previously used by the Birmingham General Hospital, as the Diana, Princess of Wales Children's Hospital – in honour of Diana, Princess of Wales, who had died the year before.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The opening ceremony was carried out by the Queen.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] In 2007, a new extension designed by RPS Group was opened.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The extension created a burns unit, one of three such centres of excellence in the country.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] As well as this, it established an outpatients department, a neonatal ward, a burns operating theatre, as well as additional classrooms for the Education Centre, allowing children to continue their education whilst undergoing medium to long-term care in the hospital.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The trust led a consortium of organisations called **Forward Thinking Birmingham** commissioned to provide mental health services for young people in the city up to the age of 25 from April 2016.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] Services for adults were previously provided by Birmingham and Solihull Mental Health NHS Foundation Trust.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] In 1970, surgeons completed the first separation of conjoined twins at the hospital.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The hospital was managed by the Birmingham Children's Hospital NHS Trust until 2017 when it merged with the Women's Hospital NHS Foundation Trust to create the Birmingham Women's and Children's NHS Foundation Trust.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The trust was named by the *Health Service Journal* as one of the top hundred NHS trusts to work for in 2015.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] At that time it had 3236 full-time equivalent staff and a sickness absence rate of 3.39%.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] 89% of staff recommend it as a place for treatment and 74% recommended it as a place to work.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The Trust's Professor Anita Macdonald, Consultant Paediatric Dietitian was awarded an OBE for services to Dietetics in the Queen's Birthday Honours 2015.
[src:birmingham-children-s-hospital/birmingham-children-s-hospital] In 2016, it became the first children's hospital to be rated Outstanding by the Care Quality Commission.
